Kaggle Community Olympiad
Host competitions and create hands-on learning opportunities
Organizer Guide
Updated on Feb 14, 2025
AI Developer Programs
About
What Is the Kaggle Community Olympiad, and Why Do We Do This?
The former ML Olympiad has now become an evergreen campaign, Kaggle Community Olympiad. This
initiative consists of a series of Kaggle Community Competitions organized by the Google AI
Community, with support from the Google AI Developer Programs team. Its goal is to foster impactful
community competitions on Kaggle, providing developers with opportunities to learn through hands-on
AI/ML experience.
To ensure a smooth transition, we are kicking off this campaign as a 6-month pilot program.
Anyone can start participating at any time, and the results have to be reported within the program
period, by the end of August 2025.
Overview
How does Kaggle Community Olympiad work?
Host a community competition that offers real-world problem-solving experience to both community
members and others. Here’s how to get started:
Plan a competition with a deﬁned problem, datasets, scoring, prizes and other settings.
Launch the competition using the name “Kaggle Community Olympiad - Your Competition Name”.
Notify the team by submitting the Registration form.
Promote the competition (Option #1) Host a training session on how to participate in your competition.
Close the competition (Option #2) Host a tech talk on winning solutions.
Report the results and claim your reward by submitting the Report form.
(Report the results right after the competition ﬁnishes. The deadline of the campaign is August 31 UTC 23:59)
Campaign Eligibility Criteria
Competitions that qualify for support should meet as followings:
Name the competition in this format: “Kaggle Community Olympiad - [Your Competition Name]”
Include this hashtag on the competition page for promotion/SEO: #KaggleCommunityOlympiad
The competition must have a unique subject (no copied competition pages) and remain active
during the open period.
The competition must have at least 20 participants.
The competition must run for at least 2 weeks (1-2 months recommended).
Before reporting the results, a training session or tech talk related to the competition must be held.
A slide deck or YouTube link must be submitted as proof.
Where can I prepare a dataset?
Use existing public datasets on Kaggle.
External Sources:
Google Dataset Search: Filter by criteria like license, format, keywords, and more.
Data.gov: The U.S. government's open data portal housing datasets from various federal agencies. Great for public policy,
statistics, and environmental data.
World Bank Open Data: Access over 20,000 datasets on development topics like education, health, poverty, and more.
UNdata: Get statistics and indicators from the United Nations on topics like population, trade, education, and environment.
Papers with Code: Explore datasets mentioned in recent research papers with links to download and code
implementations.
UC Irvine Machine Learning Repository: A well-known collection of machine learning datasets.
Competition Setup
Review the Community Competition Setup Guide:
Prepare a well deﬁned problem and datasets.
Enter a descriptive title in the format: “Kaggle Community
Olympiad - Your Competition Name”, and click the “Create a
Community Competition” button.
Set up descriptions, general settings, datasets, scoring, prizes, and
other settings.
Once you have conﬁgured all settings, go to “Host > Launch
Checklist” and review everything.
Set a launch date or launch it right away.
Notify the AI Developer Programs team that your competition has
launched by submitting this form.
Promotion
Attracting participants to your Kaggle community competition requires a mix of planning, promotion, and
community engagement:
Use the design asset package to brand and publicize your event.
Promote your competition in relevant Kaggle discussion forums.
Offer training sessions, tutorials, or starter notebooks to help beginners get started.
Be responsive to questions and comments from participants in the discussion tab.
Inform the team when your competition launches. After review, it may be featured in Kaggle’s
newsletter.
Host Tech talks
Engage your community with learning opportunities. Host a training session or follow-up sessions to
support participants and enhance their experience. You can:
Host a training session for your community members to participate in.
Host a tech talk showcasing the winning solutions.
Explore other creative ways to engage participants and share knowledge.
Example: Machine Learning São Paulo hosted a follow-up tech talk sharing the top 3 teams' solutions and
insights (video)
Report
Notify the AI Developer Programs of your competition launch
Inform the team when the competition has launched by using this form.
Report the results and claim your reward
Report the results after the competition ends. If your competition qualifies for a reward, please submit
your results using this form.
Rewards
The competition host that who has run a community competition and hosted an additional learning
session will receive:
3 Kaggle Community Olympiad T-shirts
3 Kaggle Community Olympiad Medals
A pack of badges and stickers
Additionally, 3 extra swag items will be included for sharing behind-the-scenes stories about running the
competition, such as impactful moments, inspiring experiences, or contributions to community building
and growth.
Reward Policy
Both individual members and community organizers can participate in the campaign.
The competition page, the proof of training session (video or slides) must be original creations
made in 2025.
Communities and individuals are eligible for only one reward per campaign per calendar year.
Duplicate rewards for the same campaign within a year, even if it's hosted multiple times, will not be
awarded.
*If you are an individual contributor and belong to a registered community in the Google AI Community Network, your participation will be
counted as part of the community’s involvement to avoid duplicate rewards. As a result, the community will not be eligible to claim
additional rewards for the same campaign within the same year.
Campaign Design Assets
The design assets can be used on the competition page or
your proﬁle picture. When using the designs on a landing
page, please include the following clause:
"Kaggle Community Olympiad is a series of Kaggle
Community Competitions organized by the Google AI
Community, supported by Google AI Developer Programs."

Tips from the Kaggle Competition Hosting Forum
Community Competition Prizes
Community competition hosts can now offer up to $10k in prizes for competitions they run on Kaggle.
*The AI Developer Programs team does not support prizes for community competitions.
AI Generated Competitions
You can create a competition with synthetic datasets.
Updates to Kaggle Competition Rules Template
Best Practice for Data Science Competitions from a 7x Competition Host
The Learning Agency Lab released a report on how to structure and run a data science competition.
Private Competitions
The host can control who can see and access their competition.
Notes
The campaign follows Kaggle’s Terms; see “The Rules for Competitions” for more details.
Ensure that all actions comply with the Code of Conduct.
The campaign is currently a pilot program running by August 2025 before launching as a
year-round campaign.
The goal of the campaign and reward conditions may be subject to change after the pilot program.
For scalability and openness, using open-licensed datasets is recommended, but you must strictly
adhere to each dataset’s terms of use and license. Always clearly display the data source,
acquisition process, and any modifications in your work. You are solely responsible for the datasets
you choose and how you use them.
Still need help for hosting competitions? Use Kaggle Competition Hosting Forum or Email your
questions to ml-community-organizers@googlegroups.com. Experienced hosts may be able to
help, or the answer will be shared from the Kaggle team if there’s a known issue.
FAQs
Can I open the community competition only for my community?
Yes, the competition you create can be either “open to everyone” or “invitation only.”
Is there any direct support for participants in my competition?
Unfortunately no. Please understand that the initial purpose of the campaign is to create more AI/ML learning opportunities
for developers.
As an individual contributor, not as a community organizer, can I participate in the
campaign?
Yes, it’s possible. However, when you claim the reward, if you belong to one of the registered communities in the Google AI
Community Network, your participation will be counted as part of the community’s involvement to avoid duplication of
rewards.
Can I create a competition using AI-generated competitions or the cloneable competition
feature?
You can create a community competition using the provided features, but it must have a unique subject (no copied
competition pages). Ideally, deﬁne a problem based on your own original idea, prepare datasets from scratch if possible,
consider diverse scoring metrics, and design creative tasks.
For example, in the ML Olympiad 2024, TFUG Surabaya collected and created their own dataset from Google Reviews,
preparing a dataset with over 1,000 values. Galsen AI introduced the ‘French to Wolof Translation’ challenge, which
addresses ultimately advancing the accessibility and usability of the language technology in multilingual contexts.
